		<div class="post" id="post-2028308">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2028308)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2028308">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bilgewater" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1886188); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1886188&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252506" alt="Bilgewater" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1886188)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bilgewater" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1886188); return false;" >Bilgewater</a></span> <span class="odate time_1399570914 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 May 2014 17:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2028308">
									

<p>D-8432 says 'fuck' way too much for a man his forties. I'm guessing you wanted to demonstrate how incompetent he is, but no one, except maybe a twelve-year-old who just discovered the word, swears this much, even in fear. By overusing 'fuck' you rob it of its power. It's a strong word and it deserves respect. Sure, you can have him throw it in casually here and there, but it doesn't do much to raise tension by having him constantly saying &quot;Fuckfuckfuckfuckfuck,&quot; especially where it doesn't belong. I mean, this guy was at least a Class C. Sure, he probably hasn't seen the really scary shit, but he'd be used to working in this setting and being a professional.</p>
<p>His very first line sets up how bad the rest will be. &quot;It's fucking dark.&quot; That doesn't flow and doesn't sound good when spoken. No one would say this. At least &quot;goddamn dark&quot; has some kind of alliterative pacing to it, but &quot;It's fucking dark,&quot; sounds like something a valley girl would say in a dark room.</p>
<p>I can see there's limited room for characterization in this brief dialogue and you want the character to have some kind of voice. But it feels forced and turns him into a caricature of a bumbling dope.</p>

							</div>

								
					
