			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2341089">
									

<p>I agree with Bilgewater, even so. Okay, yes, he's nervous, and it's more understandable once he sees SCP-087-01, but he's only <em>not</em> cursing in 3/8ths of his sentences. So, barring use of amnesiacs, he's either a former scientist, who therefore would presumably be a little better put-together (mentally) to be using this much profanity, or a former agent/guard, in which case he's almost certainly seen things more terrifying than a dark staircase with some luminosity anomalies. I could even see it as a joke among agents: &quot;Oh no, the SCP is playing with the lights again. SPOOKY!&quot;</p>
<p>In general, as far as I know, D-class aren't generally told about the nature of SCPs, so unless pre-demotion he already knew about SCP-087, all he knows is &quot;it's dark;&quot; nothing about it being infinite, nothing about SCP-087-01.</p>
<p>Having profanity? Sure, sounds perfectly reasonable. As much as he has? It both seems unrealistic and I feel interrupts the flow of the document. Also, fills the trope of &quot;D-class who swears in every other sentence,&quot; one I feel we should move away from.</p>
<p>That aside, I like the tale, it succinctly creates the atmosphere surrounding the SCP. Just think it could be cleaned up a little.</p>
<p>I'm aware the comment thread necromancy is a faux pas, but Bilgewater said pretty much everything I was going to, felt it would just be cluttering.</p>

							</div>

								
